<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Starting a New Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to create a new UCM mission file, configure mission information, load map/light files, and prepare the editor for event point placement.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Creating a New Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To start a new mission, select <Bold>File → New</Bold> or press
        <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>. This creates a new active
        <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.UCM</Run>
        mission file.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        A newly created mission has no event points by default. The viewport may also be empty until
        a map is loaded for display.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_new_file.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Mission Info Panel
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        When a mission is active, the <Bold>Mission Info</Bold> panel appears on the left. This
        panel summarises the mission-level data stored in the UCM file.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_mission_info_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,2">The Mission Info panel contains:</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Mission Name</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The name of the mission.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Brief</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Older mission brief field. This is no longer the main briefing source because mission briefing text is now handled through the storyboard <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">.STY</Run> file.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Map</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The map file loaded when the mission starts.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Light Map</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The light file loaded when the mission starts.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Version</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The mission file version. This editor supports mission version <Run FontFamily="Consolas" Foreground="#E8B84B">10</Run>.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Event Points</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The number of event points currently in the mission file.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Crime Rate</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls how often bad guys spawn or appear in mission/world logic.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Civilians</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Controls the number of civilians that appear on the map.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Boredom Rate</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears to be related to civilians or AI behaviour, but its exact purpose is not fully understood.</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Music</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Sets the music number for the world. This appears to be unused in the modern workflow.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,8,0,0">
        To edit the mission-level properties, click the <Bold>Edit</Bold> button in the Mission Info
        panel, adjust the fields, and save the changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_mission_properties_edit.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Missions Are Event Point Driven
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Mission files are built around Event Points. Every action, objective, sub-objective, item,
        enemy, message, trigger, cutscene, timer, bonus, and ending is tied to event point data in
        some way.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Event points can be linked and grouped together to create mission sequences. For example,
        one event point may create an enemy, another may display a message, another may count how
        many enemies have been defeated, and another may end the mission when the objective is
        complete.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Think of Event Points as mission building blocks:</Run>
                <Run>
                    each one does something specific, and complex mission logic is created by linking many of them together.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Filters Panel
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Typical mission files can contain well over 200 event points. To make this manageable, the
        editor includes a <Bold>Filters</Bold> panel.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Event points can be grouped by colour, letter group, and event point type. Filtering allows
        you to focus on only the event points relevant to the current task.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Colour filter</Bold> — limits the view to a specific colour/group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Letter group filter</Bold> — limits the view to a specific letter grouping.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Event Point Type filter</Bold> — limits the view to a selected event point type.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Some colour and letter groupings are also important for correct event point linking, so the
        filters are useful for both navigation and validation.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_filters_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Loading a Map for Editing
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A brand new mission does not require a map to technically contain event points, but editing
        without a map is difficult. You will not have visual reference for roads, buildings, objects,
        or correct placement locations.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Click the <Bold>Map</Bold> quick action button and select the map file you want to use for
        the mission. The map loads into the viewport. As with the Map Editor, map layers such as
        textures, buildings, and objects can be switched on or off.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_load_map_button.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_map_loaded.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Loading a Light File
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Click the <Bold>Lights</Bold> quick action button and select the light file you want to use.
        This loads the light data onto the map view.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        By default, light layers may be switched off. Enable the <Bold>Lights</Bold> and
        <Bold>Ranges</Bold> layer buttons if you want to see individual light entries and their
        ranges on the map.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_load_lights_button.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_lights_loaded.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Saving the Map and Light File Names into the Mission
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Loading a map or light file into the viewport is not the same as saving those filenames into
        the UCM mission file. The viewport can display arbitrary files for editing reference.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To make the mission actually use those files in game, expand the <Bold>Loaded Files</Bold>
        section in the Mission Info panel and confirm the filenames. Then click <Bold>Edit</Bold> in
        the Mission Info panel and enter the correct map and light file names into the relevant
        mission property fields. Click <Bold>Save</Bold> to store them in the mission file.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_start_loaded_files_section.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    If you only load a map or light file for display but do not save the filenames into Mission Properties,
                    the mission may not load the intended files in game.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic New Mission Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>File → New</Bold> or press <Bold>Ctrl+N</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Review the Mission Info panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Load the map using the <Bold>Map</Bold> quick action button.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Load the light file using the <Bold>Lights</Bold> quick action button.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Enable any map, mission, or light layers needed for editing.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Edit Mission Info and save the map/light filenames into the mission properties.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Begin adding event points.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

</FlowDocument>
